                <div type="commentary">
                
                <p>All commentators have considered this stele as listing military officers, because of its obvious similarities with other lists mentioning some military duties (<ref type="inscription" source="#IGCyr2">IGCyr014800</ref>, 
                   <ref type="inscription" source="#IGCyr2">IGCyr014900</ref>, <ref type="inscription" source="#IGCyr2">IGCyr015000</ref>, <ref type="inscription" source="#IGCyr2">IGCyr084000</ref>). The most striking resemblance lies in the columnar disposal and lettering.
                It should however be stressed that lists of names may correspond to other purposes. <bibl><ptr target="#rosamilia2023"/>, p. <citedRange>70</citedRange></bibl> warns in turn on this point.</p>
	      <p> A date in the second half of fourth century was already suggested in <bibl><ptr target="#IGCyr"/></bibl>, <foreign xml:lang="la">contra</foreign> <bibl><ptr target="#laronde1987"/>, p. <citedRange>133</citedRange></bibl> 
	          (<foreign xml:lang="fr">«IVe siècle sans plus de précision»</foreign>) and <bibl><ptr target="#fraser-matthews1987"/></bibl> («III BC», probably after Blass, whose argument about the name <foreign xml:lang="grc">Σμυρναῖος</foreign> did 
	          not seem binding). <bibl><ptr target="#rosamilia2023"/></bibl> reduces this span of time to ca. 330/300 BC without clear explanation.</p>
                <p>We restored the name of the first man mentioned at line 27 by comparison with <ref type="inscription" source="#IGCyr2">IGCyr095200</ref>, a dedication by a priest of Apollo of that name. 
                The dedication, hence the priesthood, is now dated to the years 290 BC by <bibl><ptr target="#rosamilia2023"/>, p. <citedRange>102</citedRange></bibl>. It 
                seems not impossible that we have here to do with the same man, if he was enlisted rather young.</p>
                <p>The name at line 14 was tentatively restored by Marengo on the basis of another tentative restoration at <ref type="inscription" source="#IGCyr2">IGCyr014300</ref>, line 6, 
                which we eventually prefer not to push forward (Eukles would also be possible there).</p>
                </div>
